  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="TK4">
<l>vēṇṭutal vēṇṭāmai yilāṉaṭi cērntārkku</l>
<l>yāṇṭu miṭumpai yila</l>            
            </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>To those united with the feet of Him for Whom there is neither</l>
<l>liking nor dislike, pain never comes.</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>
  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <head>Parimēlaḻakar</head>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="TK4-P1">
          (i-ḷ). oruporuḷaiyum viḻaitalum veṟuttalum illātava ṉaṭiyaic cērntārk kekkālattum piṟivit
          tuṉpaṅkaḷ uḷavākā.
        </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">
          The meaning ... : For those who have joined the feet of Him for Whom there is neither desiring nor hating
          even a single thing, the sufferings [that are an inherent consequence] of birth do not exist
          at any time.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="TK4-P2">
          piṟivittuṉpaṅkaḷāvana:—taṉṉaippaṟṟi varuvaṉavum, piṟavuyirkaḷaippaṟṟi varuvaṉavum,
          teyvattaippaṟṟi varuvaṉavum eṉa mūvakaiyāṉ varuntuṉpaṅkaḷ. aṭicērntārk kavviraṇṭu
          miṉmaiyiṉ, avaikāraṇamākavaru mūvakaittuṉpaṅkaḷum ilavāyiṉa.
        </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">
          The sufferings of birth are sufferings that come in three kinds—namely those that come as
          a result of one's own constitution (lit. that come about oneself), those that come as a
          result of other living beings, and those that come as a result of fate. Because those two
          [namely desiring and hating?] do not exist for those who have joined the feet, the
          sufferings of three kinds that come when those [two] exist [as their] cause(?) also cease
          to exist.
        </p>
      </div>
    </body>
  </text>
  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <head>Maṇakkuṭavar (6)</head>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="TK4-Mvar">
          <l>vēṇṭutal vēṇṭāmai yilāṉaṭi cērntār</l>
          <l>yāṇṭu miṭumpai yilar</l>
        </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
        <l>Those united with the feet of Him for Whom there is neither</l>
        <l>liking nor dislike, have no pain.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="TK4-M1">
          i - ḷ:—iṇpamum vekuḷiyum illātāṉatu tiruvaṭiyaic cērntavar evviṭattum tuṉpam illātavar.
        </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">
          The meaning ... : They who have joined the holy feet of Him for Whom there is neither pleasure nor displeasure are they who are without suffering in every [circumstance].
        </p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="TK4-M2">
          kāmamum kōpamum ākā eṉṟaṟku “vēṇṭutal vēṇṭāmaiyillāṉ” eṉṟu peyariṭṭār.
        </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">
          To [express the idea?] that there is neither passion (kāma) nor anger (kopa) [for Him], [Tiruvaḷḷuvar] has christened [the deity] as "Him for Whom there is neither liking nor dislike."
        </p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="TK4-M3">
          itu, kaiyāṟu keṭumeṉṟatu.
        </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">
          This [verse amounts to saying?] that affliction perishes [for those who worship the deity?].
        </p>
      </div>
    </body>
